   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="edition">
            <ab>
               <lb n="1"/>
               <expan><abbr>D</abbr><ex>is</ex></expan>
               <expan><abbr>M</abbr><ex>anibus</ex></expan>
               <lb n="2"/>
               <persName>
                  <name key="Sextus" type="praenomen">
                     <expan><abbr>Sex</abbr><ex>ti</ex></expan>
                  </name>
                  <name key="Flavius" type="gentilicium">Flavi</name>
                  <lb n="3"/>
                  <name key="Pancarpus" type="cognomen">Pancarpi</name>
               </persName>
               <lb n="4"/>
               <expan><abbr>q</abbr><ex>ui</ex></expan>
               <expan><abbr>vix</abbr><ex>it</ex></expan>
               <expan><abbr>ann</abbr><ex>is</ex></expan>
               <num type="cardinal" value="67">LXVII</num>.
            </ab>
         </div>
         <div type="translation">
            <p>To the divine spirits of Sextus Flavius Pancarpus, who lived 67 years.</p>
         </div>
         <div type="commentary">
            <p>Despite the fact that the inscription mentions only a man, the lunettes at the sides
                    show both male (globe and box of scrolls) and female (mirror and spindle)
                    attributes, indicating that the chest also may have contained the remains of
                    Pancarpus’ wife (MMA).</p>
                   <p>In March of 2026, this inscription and a modern forgery of a Latin epitaph, NY.NY.MMA.L.1996.228-mdn, both gifts to the MMA of Michael Finkelstein and Sue-Ann Friedman and both acquired by them from Swiss art dealer Frieda Tchacos of Galerie Nefer in Zurich, were deaccessioned and repatriated to the Republic of Italy following an investigation by Manhattan District Attorney Alvin Bragg.</p>
         </div>
